Your pipeline is powerful but heavy — running HYDE, multi-query, decomposition,
and re-ranking on every single query may:
• Increase compute cost (too many retrievals).
• Slow down responses.
• Overcomplicate simple queries.
 Self-RAG adds intelligence in deciding when and how much retrieval is needed,
instead of always doing the full pipeline.
 How Self-RAG Fits Into Your Pipeline
Think of Self-RAG as a controller layer that sits above your modules (HYDE, multiquery, decomposition, re-ranking).
Step 1: Initial Self-Assessment
• The LLM checks:
o “Is this query vague?” → If yes → use HYDE.
o “Is this query complex/multi-intent?” → If yes → use query
decomposition.
o “Could this query have multiple interpretations?” → If yes → apply multiquery retrieval.
o “Is it straightforward?” → Retrieve directly (skip heavy steps).
Step 2: Dynamic Retrieval Decisions
• After the first retrieval, Self-RAG reflects:
o “Do I have enough evidence to answer?”
▪ If yes → go to re-ranking → answer.
▪ If no → trigger more queries (multi-query or HYDE if not already
used).
Step 3: Iterative Reflection
• Self-RAG can loop:
o Retrieval → Reflection → (Optional More Retrieval).
o Stops when confidence threshold is met (e.g., ≥85% relevance in reranking).
Step 4: Final Answer with Source Control
• The LLM not only synthesizes but also:
o Marks which docs were most trusted.
o Filters out noise/conflicts.
o Outputs citations for transparency.
 Example in Practice
User Query: “Why does my father have headache after pneumonia treatment with
antibiotics?”
• Step 1 (Self-RAG check):
o Query is multi-intent (symptom cause + medication side-effect).
o Triggers query decomposition.
• Step 2 (Retrieve):
o Sub-query 1 → “Causes of headache in pneumonia recovery.”
o Sub-query 2 → “Antibiotics for pneumonia side effects (headache).”
• Step 3 (Reflection):
o Retrieval finds both: (a) residual infection, (b) common antibiotic side
effect.
o Self-RAG reflects: “Both are valid; I must mention both possibilities.”
• Step 4 (Final):
o Synthesizes → “Headache after pneumonia treatment may be due to (1)
ongoing inflammation, or (2) antibiotics such as X causing headache as a
side effect. Consult a doctor if persistent.”
o Adds citations from reliable medical sources.
 Efficiency Gains
• Skip Unnecessary Steps → If query is simple like “What is pneumonia?”, no
HYDE or decomposition needed.
• Adaptive Retrieval → Runs extra steps only when confidence is low.
• Cost Control → Fewer wasted API calls and embeddings.
• Higher Trust → The system explains why it did more retrieval.
 In short: Your pipeline + Self-RAG = Smart, Efficient, Trustworthy AI Diagnosis
